body:
Currently, Verilator translates non blocking assignments into the folowing general sequence:

```
void _eval() {
   vlSyms->__Vdly__x = vlSyms->x;
    <possible, but not necesasry assignments to vlSyms->__Vdly__x>;
   vlSyms->x = vlSyms->__Vdly_x;
}
````

There are no assignments to the `__Vdly__*` signals anywhere outside of `_eval`, so the initial `__Vdly__x = x;` (the `AstAssignPre` created in V3Delayed) is redundant except on the very first invocation. We can instead execute the `__Vdly__x = x;` at the end of the initial settle phase, and subsequently remove it from `_eval`, saving one variable copy.

Note: Currently `__Vdly__x` might have been converted into a function local, which is no longer possible with this optimization as we would then rely on the `__Vdly__*` variables being persistent across invocations of `_eval`.

Note: Right now, non blocking assignments to arrays are implemented differently (as if they were memories) and this does not apply.

Note: If the variable `x` is also assigned via blocking assignments, then we need to keep the current behaviour.
